IBM History: From Cheese Cutter to World Flights
The company IBM (International Business Machines), founded a hundred years ago in New York, initially had a rather complicated name - Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It did not take over the name IBM until 1924 - it was originally a matter of a trademark name for a branch in Canada and South America.
The foundation for the later company IBM was laid by the merger of four companies, their history until the 1980s. dates back.
They had technologies such as the famous ticket watches to register the start and end of work.
Charles Ranlett Flint, who also served as the chairmanship of the supervisory board until 1930, became the architect of this new company.
And it was Flint who headed the competing company Thomas J. Watson stopped to help him with the management of the company.
This leader then even outsshined the founders of IBM - Watson's ideas are still based on the company's invincible culture and identity today.
Watson headed the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name suggests, began to produce and distribute all possible machines for retail - from sausage and cheese tailoring, to cash registers.
In the first four decades in which Watson managed the company, he doubled its sales to nine million dollars and the company gradually expanded to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable for the company that he sat in the executive chair forty years, only then was he replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, IBM technicians and computers helped NASA's IBM to lead flights into space - to Mercury and Saturn and in 1969 also the famous flight of man to the moon.
Meanwhile, IBM developed the first computer family with the same computer architecture in 1964 - the IBM System/360 series.
A classic PC that determined the computer standard of the time came on the market in 1981 under the name IBM 5150.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, but on the other hand it bought the consultant part of the company PricewaterhouseCoopers and thus fully entered the business with consulting services and services with high added value.
The strategy that IBM is paying off over the last three years is the concept of "Smarter Planet".
It embodies the intention to use technologies in a wise manner in uneven planned areas, e.g. to improve the situation in traffic and city administration.
In the retail sector, IBM recently introduced the "Smarter Commerce" platform, which is intended to help traders manage the entire commercial cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in the Czech Republic.
As early as 1932, IBM founded a branch in the then Czechoslovakia - as the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The headquarters for Central and Eastern Europe is located in Prague, where there is also a top world-class research team that deals with the technology of voice recognition.
