Development of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, there were only five state travel agencies granted in the former SSR: Ã...edok, sports director, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
At that time, the travel agencies merely sold travel to the socialist Eastern Bloc countries, and at that time they were only allowed to go to the West.
And so Czech tourists travelled to the Baltic Sea (to the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), to the Sochi on the Crimean peninsula on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea and to Hungary to Lake Balaton.
One light exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when one was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia took a pro-Western course and therefore the trips to Yugoslavia were severely restricted.
It was a great paradox of those socialist times that it was not even citizens of the Eastern Bloc (also the Czechoslovaks) allowed to travel freely within the framework of the socialist countries.
If, for example, a citizen of the Czechoslovakia wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, then he needed a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual trips were not possible.
Even then, the travel agencies also offered travel to the West, but then you had to accept huge lines or even stay overnight in the sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
Even so, the matter had not gone.
The so-called. Foreign currency commitment - the condition for leaving the West - was only given "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so it would have been impossible to find the necessary funds (Western currency) for a trip to the West without a foreign currency.
The weathersomes therefore spent their holidays inland, no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and Datschen - a habit that continues to this day.
The Velvet Revolution of 1989 followed a travel revolution of the Czechs on the foot.
While holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria were the measure of all things until 1989, the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their holidays abroad in countries around the world last year.
A huge paradox, which one is no longer aware today, is the fact that one could not travel to the currently most popular holiday destination in the Czechs - Croatia until 1989, because it was part of the then Yugoslavia.
Right from the beginning of the 1990s, the obligation to currency to the neighbouring Western European countries was abolished, which caused a huge wave of short visits, especially to Vienna, Austria and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks simply could not get enough of their travels to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to have been there for at least a few days.
The Czech holidaymakers slept in the tent in the park when travelling to Paris, because who would have had the money for a place to stay in the hotel or in a guesthouse.
A typical feature of Czech travel abroad was a trunk packed with canned food, beer and permanent sausage, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech crown - after decades, our tourists were finally able to buy the Western currency freely.
Our standard of living, and the average salary, increased, which ended in 1997 to another important moment.
Thanks to the increased demands for trips, travel agencies began to prepare regular trips after 1997 by means of flights, making air travel incredibly discounted compared to the past thanks to the ability to negotiate volume discounts.
At the end of the 1990s, the Czechs, with the exception of the USA, had already non-visa payments with all the highly developed countries of the world, which made travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of the "post-amten" travel occurred in 2000, when, thanks to the high demand, the first direct charter flight was made to an exotic country - to Thailand.
Since then, direct charter aircraft with Czech passengers fly to far away sunny countries every year; this year, twelve exotic destinations are flying directly from the Czech Republic.
To the 100 Tsd. Czechs travel to exotic countries every year!
Another important moment in the epoch that characterized our "post-revolutionary" development came in 2008.
On the 17th In November 2008, the USA abolished the visa requirement for Czech tourists, which definitely ranked our country among the world's highly developed countries.
In 2008, the Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) for the first time, and for the first time in their history, they gave more than 15 thousands for a single holiday stay including the costs at the holiday destination. CZK per head.
