If attention paid to the signs caused by the street surface, it would not be necessary to repair almost 200,000 potholes if the rainy season breaks out at the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (city area of the valley of Mexico), said Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at UNAM University, warned and assured that if the s.
In his lecture "Sustiny holes from a technical point of view", which he gave on the occasion of the International Year on Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible develops modified asphaltes with polymers in order to produce a mixture similar to the asphalt, but which has greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera said that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with an extremely hot climate, such as in some cities in the north of the country, to improve the behaviour of the road surface and thus avoid the appearance of potholes.
He explained that the asphalt - the heaviest part of the oil - is a hydrocarbon compound, part of which has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphaltene - and the other part a low one - the so-called Malthene. Together they give the street covering its characteristic tough elastic behaviour.
Tightening behaviour of the asphalt means that it behaves like a liquid at high temperatures of almost 180°C, at 120°C it is very viscous and almost fixed at 50°C, while it becomes fragile at very low temperatures.
"This means that the resistance of the asphalt on the roads is not uniform, but changes in one day depending on the weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," the chemical engineer explained.
The researcher at FQ noticed that the majority of the streets of Mexico City had a flexible road surface consisting of six layers of material, the last three asphalts.
Between the upper layers lie a wear layer of asphalt, which consists of small stones, which consists of small stones, bathed in asphalt.
Every single stone of this wear layer was bathed in asphalt.
When the vehicles move onto them and forces are generated, this layer allows a good distribution of forces in the road surface.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would be even better," said the chemical engineer.
"Over the wear layer," he explained, "is designed a last layer, the so-called base layer, which consists of tiny stones, i.e. sand, which was also bathed in asphalt.
Since this layer is in contact with the vehicle tyres, they need a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and it has to produce friction.
The most forces that this road surface receives and distributes, the base layer also needs an appropriate thickness and the material it is made of must be maintained.
The weather conditions, especially humidity and temperature fluctuations, are other important factors to be considered, especially the water," he said, "because it significantly affects the behaviour of the wear layer.
When the terrain becomes moist, water penetrates the layer and comes out only difficult. This causes a softening of all layers of the road surface and, as a result, the appearance of potholes.
When a pothole is created," he said, "the top layer is first removed, while the wear layer is only affected afterwards. But the damage does not occur immediately, but is a process that would have to be maintained at the initial signs by appropriate maintenance programs."
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (National Research System of Mexico) explained that the vehicle load was another important cause of the appearance of potholes. Therefore, the thickness of every layer of the road surface must always be in relation to the vehicle load and it must be ensured that this regulation is complied with in order to avoid frequent potholes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that many research was still frequent, for example, about asphalt emulsions, which are already on the market in other countries, and with which the potholes could be easily repaired without the application of high temperatures.
